<exercise id="fs-id3091422" type="problems-exercises"><problem id="fs-id2602941">    <para id="import-auto-id1586963">(a) Using Bernoulli’s equation, show that the measured fluid speed <m:math><m:mi>v</m:mi></m:math> for a pitot tube, like the one in <link target-id="import-auto-id2598838"/>(b), is given by <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>v</m:mi><m:mo stretchy="false">=</m:mo><m:msup><m:mfenced open="(" close=")"><m:mfrac><m:mrow><m:mn>2</m:mn><m:mi>ρ</m:mi><m:mo>′</m:mo><m:mi fontstyle="italic">gh</m:mi></m:mrow><m:mi>ρ</m:mi></m:mfrac></m:mfenced><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mn>1</m:mn><m:mo stretchy="false">/</m:mo><m:mn>2</m:mn></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:msup></m:mrow></m:mrow><m:mrow/><m:mo>,</m:mo></m:mrow></m:math>
where <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>h</m:mi></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math> is the height of the manometer fluid,

<m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>ρ</m:mi><m:mo>′</m:mo></m:mrow><m:mrow/></m:mrow></m:math> is the density of the manometer fluid, <m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>ρ</m:mi></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math> is the density of the moving fluid, and <emphasis effect="italics"><m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>g</m:mi></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math></emphasis> is the acceleration due to gravity. (Note that <emphasis effect="italics"><m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>v</m:mi></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math></emphasis> is indeed proportional to the square root of <emphasis effect="italics"><m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>h</m:mi></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math></emphasis>, as stated in the text.) (b) Calculate <emphasis effect="italics"><m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>v</m:mi></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math></emphasis> for moving air if a mercury manometer’s <emphasis effect="italics"><m:math><m:mrow><m:mrow><m:mi>h</m:mi></m:mrow></m:mrow></m:math></emphasis> is 0.200 m.</para></problem></exercise></section>
